{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16179"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8870"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8870"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5372"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"10058"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/99521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHuman breast milk composition changes throughout lactation, transitioning from colostrum to mature milk over several weeks postpartum. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the component with the highest proportional composition in mature human breast milk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fat","Protein","Human milk oligosaccharides","Lactose","Water-soluble vitamins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe major macronutrient components of mature human breast milk include \u003Cstrong\u003Elactose\u003C/strong\u003E (~50%), \u003Cstrong\u003Efat\u003C/strong\u003E (~40%), \u003Cstrong\u003Ehuman milk oligosaccharides\u003C/strong\u003E (~8%), and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotein\u003C/strong\u003E (~2%). \u003Cstrong\u003EWater-soluble vitamins\u003C/strong\u003E are present in trace amounts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactose is the predominant carbohydrate in breast milk and serves several important functions:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EProvides energy for the growing infant\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPromotes calcium absorption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESupports development of beneficial gut bacteria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EContributes to optimal brain development\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe composition varies somewhat between individuals and throughout the course of lactation, but lactose consistently remains the major component by proportion in mature milk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactose is the predominant carbohydrate in human breast milk, comprising approximately 50% of total caloric content.","The major components of mature human breast milk are lactose (50%), fat (40%), human milk oligosaccharides (HMOs) (8%), and protein (2%)."],"references":["Ballard O, Morrow AL. Human milk composition: nutrients and bioactive factors. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2013 Feb;60(1):49-74. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2012.10.002. PMID: 23178060; PMCID: PMC3586783.","Kim SY, Yi DY. Components of human breast milk: from macronutrient to microbiome and microRNA. Clin Exp Pediatr. 2020 Aug;63(8):301-309. doi: 10.3345/cep.2020.00059. Epub 2020 Mar 23. PMID: 32252145; PMCID: PMC7402982.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Mar 31;23(7):3883. doi: 10.3390/ijms23073883. PMID: 35409243; PMCID: PMC8998991"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-21T11:30:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-21T11:31:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8870"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"99521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https:/